            <DIV class=3Dblog_subject>ISO committee takes full control =
of OOXML<A=20
            name=3Dentry080409-221633>&nbsp;</A> </DIV><!-- BLOG TITLE =
END --><!-- BLOG BODY BEGIN -->
            <DIV class=3Dblog_body>
            <DIV class=3Dblog_date>2008-04-09, 22:16</DIV><A=20
            =
href=3D"http://picasaweb.google.co.uk/alexander.david.john.brown/Iso/phot=
o#5187934333447694178"><IMG=20
            =
src=3D"http://lh5.ggpht.com/alexander.david.john.brown/R_8-yhcz52I/AAAAAA=
AAAeI/woIk1W1b-LA/s400/harmony.jpg"></A><BR><I>Harmony?=20
            Patrick Durusau, Jean Paoli and Brian Jones</I><BR><BR>Since =
my last=20
            blog entry a lot has happened. The big story of course is =
that DIS=20
            29500 gathered enough votes to pass as an International =
Standard.=20
            Although the margin of votes in its favour was (surprisingly =
to me)=20
            reasonably comfortable, the overall mood of acceptance seems =
less of=20
            a "yip yip yahoo!" and perhaps more of a "well, alright". =
Everybody=20
            is now watching very carefully ...<BR><BR>
            <H1>Resolutions</H1><BR>Now however, the whole process moves =
forward=20
            into a much more significant stage. At the just-finished <A=20
            =
href=3D"http://www.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/sc34/open/0976draft-rev3.htm"=20
            target=3D_blank>SC 34 meeting in Oslo</A> a number of <A=20
            href=3D"http://www.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/sc34/open/1025.htm"=20
            target=3D_blank>resolutions</A> were passed relating to =
29500. The=20
            most significant of these is resolution 4, "Creation of Ad =
Hoc Group=20
            1 on ISO/IEC 29500 Maintenance", and it's worth looking at =
it in=20
            some detail. I will go through the complete resolution below =
with=20
            some explanation of my own ...<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: =
#ddf"><B>Background</B><BR><BR>SC=20
            34 is the JTC 1 designated maintenance body for ISO/IEC =
29500=20
            (Office Open XML file formats). </DIV><BR>simply states the =
fact=20
            that JTC 1 have handed full responsibility for the standard =
over to=20
            SC 34. We then have some informative text setting out SC =
34's=20
            current orientation:<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ddf">The=20
            passage of ISO/IEC 29500 has instituted a new era of =
standards=20
            activity in SC 34 related to document formats. ISO/IEC 29500 =
does=20
            not represent an isolated phenomenon, since SC 34 is also=20
            responsible for ISO/IEC 26300 and for interoperability =
between these=20
            and other projects.<BR><BR>SC 34 envisages the creation of =
three=20
            distinct working groups that meet the needs of:=20
            <OL>
              <LI>ISO/IEC 29500=20
              <LI>ISO/IEC 26300=20
              <LI>Work on interoperability/harmonization between =
document format=20
              standards </LI></OL>and wishes to incorporate existing =
expertise on=20
            these standards.<BR><BR>For these reasons, SC 34 hereby =
establishes=20
            an ad hoc group pursuant to the JTC 1 Directives, clause =
2.6.2, for=20
            investigating how the first of these groups may be set up =
most=20
            effectively. </DIV><BR>So, SC 34 has a plan: it envisages =
taking=20
            control of OOXML, then setting up a maintance procedure for =
ODF, and=20
            then working on cross-standard initiatives. As the first =
part of=20
            effecting this plan it is setting up a temporary group (in =
ISO=20
            parlance an "ad hoc group") to <B>investigate how</B> OOXML =
can be=20
            maintained. The rest of the resolution sets out the terms of =

            reference for this new investigative group.<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: =
#ddf"><B>Terms=20
            of Reference</B><BR><BR>The terms of reference for the group =
are as=20
            follows: </DIV><BR>The first of these terms of reference set =
out the=20
            task that the group is to perform:<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ddf">The=20
            task to be completed by the group is to <B>advise its =
convenor</B>=20
            on creation of a document proposing structures and =
mechanisms for=20
            onward work on ISO/IEC IS29500. Onward work is defined =
as:<BR>
            <UL>
              <LI>Maintenance as provided for by the JTC 1 Directives =
(in=20
              particular Section 15 - Maintenance of International=20
Standards)<BR>
              <LI>Handling new work items directly and exclusively =
related to=20
              ISO/IEC IS29500 (e.g. creation of new Parts of this =
Standard or=20
              evolution of this standard)<BR></LI></UL>
            <P>The proposal shall be drafted by the convenor as one or =
more=20
            resolutions (with supporting explanatory material) that may =
be=20
            discussed, revised and adopted by SC 34.<BR></P>
            <P>The ad hoc group should consider the following factors in =
making=20
            its recommendations to the convenor:<BR></P>
            <OL>
              <P>a) A new working group should be created in SC 34 for =
the=20
              purpose of maintenance of ISO/IEC 29500 pursuant to =
Section 15 of=20
              the JTC 1 Directives for standards maintenance.<BR>b) =
Editors and=20
              editing teams should be nominated as well as mechanisms =
for the=20
              nomination of editors and editing teams for ISO/IEC =
29500.<BR>c)=20
              Transparency of process, consistent with JTC 1 Directives, =
is a=20
              goal of the recommended process.<BR>d) Consideration =
should be=20
              given to how Ecma and ISO/IEC versions of ISO/IEC 29500 =
may be=20
              best kept synchronized.<BR>e) The proposal should =
recommend ways=20
              in which onward work on ISO/IEC 29500 may be carried out =
in as=20
              timely a way as possible, without recourse to the =
accelerated=20
              mechanisms of PAS or Fast Track=20
            procedures.<BR></P></OL></DIV><BR>There are several things =
of note=20
            here. First is that the group activities are limited to =
OOXML only,=20
            and that the group will be purely advisory. It will advise =
its=20
            convenor who will weigh up the advice and report back to SC =
34 who=20
            will in turn make a decision that heeds (or ignores) that=20
            advice.<BR><BR>Perhaps the most interesting thing here is =
the list=20
            (items "a" to "e") in which SC 34 gives a "steer" to the =
group on=20
            how it should be thinking about OOXML maintenance. What we =
learn=20
            from this is that the group should try to come up with a =
process=20
            that ensures maintenance activities are fully staffed, as =
open as=20
            possible, that keep Ecma and ISO versions of the standard in =
sync,=20
            and which sticks to the full rigour of normal committee =
working=20
            without any Fast Track or PAS oddities.<BR><BR>The later =
clauses=20
            flesh out some important further details.<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ddf">2.=20
            The ad hoc group shall make its proposal to SC 34 for =
consideration=20
            at its plenary scheduled for 2008-10-01, at Jeju Island, =
Korea. A=20
            draft proposal shall be made available to SC 34 one month =
before the=20
            plenary. </DIV><BR>sets the duration of the work. It will =
take place=20
            over the next 6 months or so and report in time for SC 34 to =

            consider its findings at the next plenary.<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ddf">3.=20
            The ad hoc group shall be open to participation from all SC =
34=20
            members, subgroup members, and liaison bodies. Participants =
shall be=20
            nominated by these bodies to the SC 34 secretariat in the =
usual way.=20
            </DIV><BR>simply states that the usual people will be able =
to=20
            participate in the activity (SC 34 committee members, =
etc.)<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ddf">4.=20
            The ad hoc group shall be convened by Dr Alex Brown, as =
nominated by=20
            the UK National Body (BSi). </DIV><BR>says it is I who will =
be=20
            convening it - an honour indeed!<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ddf">5.=20
            Administration and support for the ad hoc group=92s =
activities shall=20
            be provided by the SC 34 Secretariat. </DIV><BR>points out =
that our=20
            super-efficient SC 34 secretariat (of the Japanese NB) will =
be=20
            providing much needed assistance.<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ddf">6.=20
            The ad hoc group shall arrange face-to-face, telephone and=20
            electronic meetings as required in accord with the =
provisions of the=20
            JTC 1 Directives. The first face-to-face meeting shall take =
place in=20
            early July in London, UK. </DIV><BR>sets out some meeting =
details.=20
            The "main event" will be a two day meeting in London in=20
            summer.<BR><BR>and ... that's it. The resolution passed with =

            unanimous support.<BR><BR>
            <H1>Bringing Ecma in</H1><BR>The above resolution says =
nothing of=20
            Ecma, since maintenance is now an SC 34 activity. =
Practically=20
            speaking, however, the Ecma TC 45 team are the guys who know =
more=20
            that anybody what is really going on with OOXML, so SC 34 =
issued a=20
            liaison statement (a fancy term for a "message") inviting =
these=20
            experts to participate:<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ddf">SC34=20
            recognizes that Ecma TC45 members have in-depth knowledge, =
technical=20
            expertise on ISO/IEC 29500 and will seek to preserve and =
allow for=20
            inclusion of this existing body of technical expertise in =
SC34. SC34=20
            therefore invite Ecma TC45 members to attend and fully =
participate=20
            in ISO/IEC JTC 1 SC 34 Ad Hoc Group 1 as well as in any =
future=20
            working group that will be dedicated to the maintenance of =
ISO/IEC=20
            29500. SC34 intends to organize an efficient and timely =
process for=20
            maintaining and handling new work items to insure the =
evolution of=20
            the standard in following the JTC 1 Directives. =
</DIV><BR><BR>This=20
            encourages inclusion of the TC 45 people -- but they will of =
course=20
            have no power of vote at any level in the process.<BR><BR>
            <H1>Short-term maintenance</H1><BR>While all this =
investigative work=20
            is going on to determine the long-term maintenance procedure =
for=20
            OOXML, there is a more pressing task: recording the defects =
that are=20
            currently known and being found in the OOXML spec. With this =
in=20
            mind, a second ad hoc group is being established for =
collections of=20
            comments.<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ddf">
            <P>ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 34 establishes Ad Hoc Group 2 in =
accordance with=20
            subclause 2.6.2 of the JTC 1 Directives, with the following =
terms of=20
            reference:<BR></P>
            <UL>
              <LI><B>Definition of the task:<BR></B>
              <UL>
                <LI>To define and put into operation a mechanism to =
compile a=20
                list of comments on ISO/IEC 29500 received from NBs, =
liaisons,=20
                and the general public.<BR>
                <LI>To publish the on-going list as an open document on =
the SC=20
                34 website.<BR></LI></UL>
              <LI><B>Time frame: </B>The collection mechanism is to =
become=20
              operational within 90 days from the end of the April 2008 =
ISO/IEC=20
              JTC 1/SC 34 plenary. Once this is operational, collection =
will=20
              continue until a long-term maintenance process is =
operational.<BR>
              <LI><B>Membership:</B> Open to ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 34 P and O =

              members, liaison organizations, and subgroup =
representatives.<BR>
              <LI><B>Convener: </B>Makoto Murata (JP).<BR>
              <LI><B>Meeting arrangements: </B>Work will be handled =
primarily by=20
              email, with optional telephone conference calls at dates =
and times=20
              to be announced.<BR></LI></UL></DIV><BR><BR>The main =
thinking here=20
            is that knowledge about defects must not get lost. This =
group, under=20
            the expert leadership of Murata Makoto, will make sure that =
does not=20
            happen, and that defects are carefully collected so that =
they might=20
            be fed into the onward maintenance process.<BR><BR>
            <H1>A little local difficulty</H1><BR>While all this work =
was going=20
            on, the OOXML backstory continued. In Norway there is a fuss =
that=20
            the NB (Standard Norway) did not adopt the recommendation of =
a=20
            technical committee. The situation was well explained by the =

            excellent Lars Marius Garshol in his <A=20
            href=3D"http://www.garshol.priv.no/blog/154.html" =
target=3D_blank>blog=20
            entry</A> preceding the Norwegian vote. I can understand the =

            crossness - I certainly would be miffed if our standards =
body (BSI)=20
            did not heed the advice of its technical committee, though =
in the UK=20
            case of course the technical committee recommended that BSI=20
            <B>approves</B> DIS 29500 ... What I find less =
understandable is how=20
            what is essentially a local spat (with SN rather obviously =
acting=20
            within its powers) has been blown up into something bigger=20
            ...<BR><BR><A=20
            =
href=3D"http://picasaweb.google.co.uk/alexander.david.john.brown/Iso/phot=
o#5187893870560798546"><IMG=20
            =
src=3D"http://lh4.ggpht.com/alexander.david.john.brown/R_8Z_Rcz51I/AAAAAA=
AAAdM/xXevtPyY4BE/s288/IMG_0079.JPG"></A><BR><I>Steve=20
            Pepper</I><BR><BR>The <A=20
            =
href=3D"http://blogs.freecode.no/isene/2008/04/09/quick-report-from-the-n=
orwegian-ooxml-demonstration/"=20
            target=3D_blank>demonstration</A> passed off reasonably =
enough ... 100=20
            or so geeks decamped from the adjacent open source =
conference to=20
            stand in the rain and wave placards while Steve Pepper had =
fun=20
            making a speech and brandishing a hairdrier (perhaps risking =
quips=20
            about 'hot air' in the process). There was some half-hearted =

            chanting ("what's that smell? OOXML!"). Meanwhile some =
on-looking SC=20
            34 people felt insulted. One neutral XML expert, who I know =
for a=20
            fact took a very close technical look at DIS 29500 asked =
"what are=20
            they saying? that we are incompetent? that we do not have =
the right=20
            to decide for ourselves?". Well ... were they?<BR><BR><A=20
            =
href=3D"http://picasaweb.google.co.uk/alexander.david.john.brown/Iso/phot=
o#5187200186699712066"><IMG=20
            =
src=3D"http://lh6.ggpht.com/alexander.david.john.brown/R_yjFjsThkI/AAAAAA=
AAAcs/kbm2jzpDk6I/s400/PICT0004.JPG"></A><BR><I>Disharmony?=20
            the anti-OOXML protest</I><BR><BR>
            <H1>Standards of behaviour</H1><BR>Perhaps the most =
extraordinary=20
            document issued by SC 34 during this Oslo meeting was an =
"open=20
            letter", which received many signatures.<BR><BR>
            <DIV=20
            style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 20px; PADDING-LEFT: 20px; =
PADDING-BOTTOM: 20px; PADDING-TOP: 20px; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ddf">We=20
            the undersigned participants at this SC 34 meeting wish to =
make it=20
            clear that we deplore the personal attacks that have been =
made=20
            during the DIS 29500 standardisation project in recent =
months. We=20
            believe standards debate should always be carried out with =
respect=20
            for all parties, even when they strongly disagree.<BR><BR>We =
call on=20
            all organisations and individuals involved in SC 34 =
standardisation=20
            to support this view, and to refrain from initiating or =
engaging in=20
            any such personal attacks. </DIV><BR>This content speaks for =

            iself.<BR clear=3Dall></DIV><!-- BLOG BODY END --><!-- BLOG =
FOOTER BEGIN -->
